## Scope

This slice is the pure geometry layer that draws the light path: one central
ray plus eight side rays, incident/reflected/transmitted ray groups,
element snapping onto the central ray, distance‑preserving downstream travel
when an element is tilted, orphaning rules, default light‑source and detector
placement, and schematic Snell tracing through tilted elements. It lives in
a new `RayModel.fs` module and carries no Avalonia type. The quantitative
result at each element still comes from the existing beam‑tree solver
(BeamTree.fs:91); the drawn branches MUST stay consistent with the
reflected/transmitted branches the engine computes (BeamTree.fs:98).

## Requirements

### R-1. Ray group: one central ray and eight side rays (B.1)

B.1.1 `RayModel.fs` MUST model a ray group as one **central ray (CR)** plus
**eight side rays**. At normal incidence the eight side rays MUST land as
equidistant points on a circle, 45° apart, with the CR striking the centre
of that circle (the "rifle‑target" pattern). The side rays MUST visibly
spread only when a lens, a non‑flat (curved) mirror, a prism, or a wedge
bends them.

B.1.2 The on‑screen radius of the eight‑ray bundle MUST be a fixed fraction
of the element's clear face: `bundle_radius = 0.4 × (face_extent / 2)`.
This fraction is a schematic legibility choice (no canonical standard
exists for ray‑bundle radius; it is anchored to the optics rule that a
clear aperture is ≈2–3× the beam, so 0.4 keeps all eight side rays clearly
inside the face — see References). It MUST be a named constant.

### R-2. Incident, reflected, transmitted groups; detector termination (B.2)

B.2.1 `RayModel.fs` MUST name the incident ray group (IRG) — the ray group
falling on an element — as the frame against which that element's rotations
are measured (A.4.3). Every element except a mirror produces both a
transmitted ray group (TRG) and a reflected ray group (RRG); a mirror
produces only an RRG. The drawn groups MUST follow the element's A.7
emission metadata and MUST correspond to the engine branches
(`Reflected`/`Transmitted`, BeamTree.fs:21).

B.2.2 A **Detector (D)** MUST terminate the ray group it receives: no
ray group is drawn leaving a detector.

### R-3. Snapping and downstream travel (B.3)

B.3.1 Each element's placement point MUST snap onto the central ray
(B.1, A.2). `RayModel.fs` MUST expose a pure function that, given a ray and
a set of elements with their placement points and rotations, produces the
drawn ray geometry with every element snapped to its ray.

B.3.2 Changing an element's R2 and/or R3 MUST change the direction of its
reflected ray R and MAY change the direction of its transmitted ray T.
Everything snapped to a ray downstream of the rotated element MUST travel
with the new ray direction **while preserving all distances** measured
along the ray. Tilting one element MUST therefore drag everything
downstream of it along the new beam direction automatically, keeping the
inter‑element spacing unchanged.

### R-4. Default light‑source and detector placement (B.4)

B.4.1 The light source MUST have a default placement near the left side of
the table, vertically centred; the detector MUST have a default placement
near the right side, vertically centred. The central ray MUST originate at
the light source and terminate at the detector, and the initial distance
between them MUST be `2.0 m`, measured along the central ray.

B.4.2 Because everything downstream is snapped to the central ray, moving
the light source MUST drag the whole chain with it. The light source MUST
expose a **position reset** (reachable from its local element menu, Part E)
that returns it to its default spot; when the light source moves or resets,
the remaining elements MUST re‑snap to the ray, preserving their along‑ray
distances.

### R-5. Orphaned elements (B.5)

B.5.1 An element MUST become *orphaned* (left without a ray) only by one of
two operations: (a) changing which ray is tracked (e.g. switching the
tracked branch from T to R), or (b) removing one ray while both R and T are
in use. Elements that were sitting on the removed ray MUST become orphaned.

B.5.2 No other operation MUST orphan an element — ordinary rotation and
dragging MUST always keep elements attached to a ray.

B.5.3 If a removed ray is later restored, an orphaned element MUST re‑snap
to it when the restored ray passes within a configured distance of the
element's placement point; otherwise the element MUST stay orphaned until
the user reattaches it. The re‑snap distance MUST be a named, configurable
constant.

### R-6. Schematic Snell tracing through tilted elements (B.6)

B.6.1 When an element has R2 ≠ 0 and/or R3 ≠ 0, the central and side rays
genuinely change direction and the side rays MAY refract. `RayModel.fs`
MUST compute the bent line geometry by applying Snell's law with `n = 1.0`
outside and `n = 1.5` inside the element (constraint 0.5). These two indices
MUST be named constants in `RayModel.fs`.

B.6.2 When both the reflected and transmitted groups are emitted, the two
MUST be drawn as distinct outgoing groups from the element's face; the
visual distinction (colour / weight / alpha) is specified in Part C.

### R-7. Consistency with the engine (B.7)

B.7.1 The reflected/transmitted groups the constructor draws MUST be the
same two branches the engine beam tree routes and solves (BeamTree.fs:98,
`:117`). The drawing MUST NOT invent a branch the engine does not compute,
and MUST NOT suppress a branch the element's A.7 metadata emits.

## Non-requirements

- No Avalonia type in this module (pure geometry; constraint 0.3).
- No physical‑optics accuracy; schematic only (constraint 0.5).
- No drawing weights / colours (Part C / slice 004) and no interaction
  gestures (Part E / slice 005) — this slice exposes pure geometry only.
- No re‑implementation of the engine solver (BeamTree.fs:91) — reuse it.

